# OmniMeet: Comprehensive Technical Audit Report

This report presents a thorough architectural, security, and performance audit of the **OmniMeet** real-time video conferencing codebase. 

---

## 1. Executive Status Summary

| Metric | Rating | Description |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Current Stability** | 🔴 **FRAGILE (Not Production-Ready)** | The application functions under ideal, single-peer transitions, but is architecturally broken for multi-peer calls due to a critical connection re-initialization flaw. |
| **Security Posture** | 🟡 **WEAK** | The application does not use actual JWTs, exposes session tokens in query parameters, lacks Socket.io connection authentication, and allows unrestricted entry into active meetings. |
| **Resource Efficiency** | 🔴 **POOR** | Contains severe client-side and server-side memory leaks (leaking PeerConnections, audio/video threads, time tracking records, and room message history). |
| **Code Polish & UX** | 🟡 **UNPOLISHED** | UX components overlap, there is styling library pollution (Bootstrap + Material UI), and the guest joining flow is completely hardcoded to a single room. |

> [!WARNING]  
> **Verdict:** The current WebRTC implementation will fail under multi-peer load, freeze existing streams, leak client browser resources, and eventually crash the Node.js server under high connection volumes. **Do not attempt to add new features until the prerequisites listed at the end of this report are implemented.**

